      "title": "Conormal Points",
      "conceptBody": "<h3><strong>Co-normal points</strong></h3><p>The points on the curve at which the normal’s pass through a common point are called Co-normal points.</p><p>$\\text{Q},\\text{R}$ and $\\text{S}$ are co-normal points. The co-normal points are also called the feet of the normal’s.</p><p><img src=\"data:image/jpeg;base64,\" width=\"193\" height=\"170\"></p><p><strong>Some results on co-normal points</strong></p><p>Let ${{\\text{y}}^{2}}=4\\text{ax}$ be a parabola and let $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$ a point. The equation of any normal to</p><p>${{\\text{y}}^{2}}=4\\text{ax}$ is</p><p>$\\text{y}=\\text{mx}-2\\text{am}-\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}^{3}}$</p><p>If it passes thought $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$, then</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {{\\text{y}}_{1}} &amp; ~=\\text{m}{{\\text{x}}_{1}}-2\\text{am}-\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}^{3}} \\\\ \\Rightarrow \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ a}{{\\text{m}}^{3}}+\\left( 2\\text{a}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)+{{\\text{y}}_{1}} &amp; ~=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>This is a cubic equation in $\\text{m}$. So, it gives three values of $\\text{m}$, say, ${{\\text{m}}_{1}},\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}},\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{3}}$.</p><p>Corresponding to each of these values of $\\text{m}$ there is a normal to the parabola passing</p><p>through point $\\text{P}\\left( {{\\text{x}}_{1}},{{\\text{y}}_{1}} \\right)$. Let $\\text{Q},\\text{R}$ and $\\text{S}$ be three points on the parabola such that the</p><p>normal’s at these points pass through $\\text{P}$. If ${{\\text{m}}_{1}},\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ and ${{\\text{m}}_{3}}$ are the slopes of the</p><p>normals at $\\text{Q},\\text{R}$ and $\\text{S}$ respectively. Then, the coordinates of $\\text{Q},\\text{R}$ and $\\text{S}$ are</p><p>$\\left( \\text{am}_{1}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{1}} \\right),\\left( \\text{am}_{2}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{2}} \\right)$ and $\\left( \\text{am}_{3}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{3}} \\right)$ respectively. These three points are</p><p>called the feet of the normals.</p><p>Now, ${{\\text{m}}_{1}},\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}$ and ${{\\text{m}}_{3}}$ are roots of (i). Therefore,</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; {{\\text{m}}_{1}}+{{\\text{m}}_{2}}+{{\\text{m}}_{3}}=0 \\\\ {} &amp; \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}+{{\\text{m}}_{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{3}}+{{\\text{m}}_{3}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{1}}=\\frac{\\left( 2\\text{a}-{{\\text{x}}_{1}} \\right)}{\\text{a}} \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p>and, ${{\\text{m}}_{1}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{2}}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{3}}=-\\frac{{{\\text{y}}_{1}}}{\\text{a}}$</p><p><strong>Result I. </strong>The sum of the slopes of the normals at co-normal points is zero.</p><p><strong>Result II. </strong>The sum of the ordinates of the co-normal points is zero.</p><p><strong>Proof : </strong>The coordinates of the feet of the normals are $\\left( \\text{am}_{1}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{1}} \\right),\\left( \\text{am}_{2}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{2}} \\right)$ and</p><p>$\\left( \\text{am}_{3}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{3}} \\right)$.</p><p>$\\therefore $ Sum of the ordinates of the co-normal points</p><p>$\\begin{array}{*{35}{r}} {} &amp; ~=-2\\text{a}\\left( {{\\text{m}}_{1}}+{{\\text{m}}_{2}}+{{\\text{m}}_{3}} \\right)=-2\\text{a }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }0 \\\\ {} &amp; ~=0 \\\\ \\end{array}$</p><p><strong>Result III. </strong>The centroid of the triangle formed by the co-normal points lies on the axis of the parabola :</p><p><strong>Proof : </strong>The vertices of the triangle formed by the co-normal points are $\\left( \\text{am}_{1}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{1}} \\right)$,</p><p>$\\left( \\text{am}_{2}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{2}} \\right)$ and $\\left( \\text{am}_{3}^{2},-2\\text{a}{{\\text{m}}_{3}} \\right)$.</p><p>So, y-coordinates of the centroid $=-\\frac{2\\text{a}}{3}\\left( \\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }{{\\text{m}}_{1}}+{{\\text{m}}_{2}}+{{\\text{m}}_{3}} \\right)$</p><p>$=-\\frac{2\\text{a}}{3}\\text{ }\\!\\!~\\!\\!\\text{ }0=0$</p><p>Hence, the centroid lies on the x-axis i.e. axis of the parabola.</p>",
      "position": 0,
      "qcConcept": "66a0dd9ec03b9dcaf1afebe4"
    }
